USDA SOLICITS FOREIGN ANIMAL DISEASE COMMITTEE NOMINATIONS
WASHINGTON, March 18, 1996--The U.S. Department of Agriculture's
Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service is seeking nominations for
membership on the Secretary's Advisory Committee on Foreign Animal
Diseases.
Members of the advisory committee serve for two years
advising USDA on actions and policies necessary to keep foreign
animal diseases of livestock and poultry, such as foot-and-mouth
disease, from being introduced into the United States. Members also
give recommendations on contigency planning and on maintaining a
state of preparedness to deal with these exotic and emerging
diseases, if accidently introduced. APHIS' veterinary services is
part of the USDA'S marketing and regulatory programs mission area.
Organizations and individuals can submit nominations to:
John Williams, chief staff veterinarian, emergency programs, VS,
APHIS, USDA, 4700 River Road, Unit 41, Riverdale, Md. 20737-1231.
The telephone number is (301) 743-8073.
This notice was published in the March 7 Federal Register.
Nominations received on or before April 22 will be
considered.
